The Taliban continued for their hatred for the Hazara famous Taliban.
Many Hazara left the country towards Pakistan or Iran.
A few days after his escape, Asharaf found himself back in Pakistan.
For a few years he worked in a cohaul. the work was heavy and made it ill.
Then he took what was left of his low wages, and went into Iran. once again he was in a foreign country along with other refugees and towed sacks with mortar that were heavier than himself, in order to make himself his living.
Back then as today, the life of Afghan refugees in Iran was influenced by misery and exploitation.
"it was really hard," Ashark remembered in an interview with Global Voices. "we (Afghan refugees) lived in an empty building on the construction site, which we also worked.
There was no services there and no heating. we put nylon in front of the open windows, so that we don't freeze it at night. "
After four years, Ashark left his life without papers in Iran and made themselves ready for the journey to Europe.
During the dangerous crossing on the sea, he suffered shipwreck and stranded on a small, uninhabited Greek island.
After the Greek authorities rejected his asylum application, Ashark came to Italy in 2002.
Some time was Asharaf homeless, ran solely through the streets of Rome, slept in parks and went to a church that divided twice a day of food in needy.
It is true that Italy due to relatively high awareness quotas is a sort of second chance for asylum seekers. it is true, however, that the conditions that asylum seekers are catastrophic in the country.
